    b.
        i.
            Let K be the weight of the lower leg in newtons.
            Force Y = 0.25K/0.35 = 0.25/0.35 * K
            Force X = 0.35/0.25 * K
            0.25/0.35 < 1 < 0.35/0.25 so force X is larger
        ii.
            Force X decreases and force Y increases as the bag is moved toward the person's foot. This is because as the bag is moved toward the person's foot, the combined centre of gravity of the bag-and-leg also moves towards the person's foot. Letting a = the perpendicular distance of the centre of gravity from support A and b = the perpendicular distance of the centre of gravity from support B, we see as in b(i) that force X = b/a * (K + weight of ice), and that force Y = a/b * (K + weight of ice). As the ice is moved towards the foot the centre of gravity also shifts towards the foot, increasing a and decreasing b. It is easy to see that this decreases force X but increases force Y.
3.
    a.

        Extra apparatus: stopwatch, balance.

        Firstly, the student should measure the mass of the water by pouring it into a beaker on a balance (zeroed on the beaker).

        The student can measure the power output of the circuit by multiplying the reading from the voltmeter with the reading from the ammeter, since voltage * current = power. The student should keep an eye on this make a reading every second. The student should take a starting reading from the thermometer and simultaneously turn on the circuit and start the stopwatch. The insulating material and lid will ensure no heat escapes, and the electrical heater will convert electrical energy into thermal energy, heating the water. When the thermometer indicates that the water has risen in temperature by ten degrees, the student should stop the stopwatch. The student can then calculate the mean power (sum of (each voltage reading * each current reading)) divided by the number of readings, and then multiply the mean power by the total amount of time the circuit was on to find the amount of energy (in joules) expended/transferred to the water over the course of the experiment. The student can then divide the amount of energy in joules by the mass in grams and the change in temperature (10 degrees) to get a value with unit Joules per kilogram-degree, which will be the specific heat capacity of water. The student should repeat this experiment three times and take the average of the results.
